,Recommended,415740,23297221,"Posted: 30 May, 2016",all,LOOK WHAT YOU MADE ME DOOOOO,"As a sarcastic anti-game,OmniBusis a masterpiece in its own right, arguably the best of its kind since landmark cult hitGoat Simulatorarrived some years back.Viewed as any other release? Positive-leaning mixed feelings.The concept of a vehicular platformer is a an exceedingly rare novelty in itself. I struggle to think of any other game that defines itself as such, much less so in the wayOmniBusdares to present itself. To consider this anything less than commendable would be a disservice.Mind you, that's not to sayOmniBusdoesn't have its shortcomings; the lack of a camera control makes certain actions harder than they really need need to be, the physics are often far more unpredictable than reasonably anticipated and while the humor works for me, others are likely to put off -- dry sarcasm is very much a love it or hate it sort of thing.The same could also be said for the game's aesthetics; early 90s throwback visuals and bouncy chiptune are right up my alley, but for those unaccustomed to a period when the average game looked and felt no different? Further disappointment.To put it simply:OmniBusisn't a game for everyone. Then again, it isn't trying to be, and maybe that's really what I like about it best, anyway."
,Recommended,415740,23227588,"Posted: 26 May, 2016",all,Gyanreyer,"This game is absolutely nowhere near perfect, but I'm finding it to be very entertaining.Basically the premise is that you're Omnibus, a bus that endlessly accelerates with no brakes that must travel the world, completing challenges and helping people along the way. Yeah, everything about this game is kinda ridiculous but it's actually incredibly funny and charming as a result.Here's the deal though, if you're not into the whole ""whacky physics challenge"" games like Surgeon Simulator or QWOP where part of the entire challenge is just fighting against the game, then you probably won't enjoy this much. Your bus can go flying at the drop of a hat and there's a lot of wrestling with physics and trying to keep your bus under control which can quickly go from funny to maddening. I've gotten stuck on a couple levels and felt quite frustrated, but in the end they don't take too much of your time to play and when you beat them it feels very satisfying, as a challenging game should.Now what's crazy is how incredibly creative the devs got - so far every single level has presented a new, unique challenge from anything before it that is still very fun and interesting, whether that be driving in a top-heavy tour bus trying not to tip over and lose your passengers or driving up the side of a building to knock King Kong off the top. It's very hard but addictive, and the ridiculous stupidity of it all just makes it that much better.With the fact that each level has a gold medal that you can shoot for and there's a local multiplayer mode that looks kinda fun, I can see this game having a ton of replay value, and I'm definitely happy with my purchase. If it looks interesting to you, I say go for it, you'll get a sense of the game pretty quick and you can easily refund if it's not your thing!"
,Not Recommended,415740,31860346,Posted: 20 May,all,Ryan Dorkoski,"On one handOmniBuscomes off at times like a total 'gimmick' joke game, but other times it teases with the possibility of being a fully realized game based on skill and maybe even real speedrunning material.I think it struggles by not taking a side, along with a price tag that merits something more beefy. If you are on the fence - play the demo - that will give you a good idea of what you are in for.The first major problem withOmniBusis that some of it is skill-based, but alot of itisn't.There were too many times where I was just flopping around with different bus mechanics to get the win. Yeah, maybe there are people out there that have devoted enough time to 'getting good' at this, but there are many,manyother more solid titles for that kind of time dump. The upside (and part that teases of a more serious game) is that nearly every level has something unique and interesting about it. There obviously was some thought put into this.Another problem is rough edges and lack of polish. Honestly, this feels like a game that was made in some weekend jam. And I'm not talking about one that started there and then had many more months of TLC and polish. It feels like a few of those 'Humble Originals' they tack onto the end of the Monthly Bundles. But it costs ten bucks. The biggest problem for me is that you cannot control the camera (ie. with the right stick, usually). So you really can't see where you are going and this adds a layer of difficulty that just feels artifical. The mechanics of the bus feel 'ok' at best, and at worst, they feel floaty and a bit too random.Pros:+I love theidea, although the execution leaves something to be desired. Trust me on this - go playRoundAboutinstead.+Music is the best part.+Level design and variation is really good.+Controller support is good, and menus are lean and functional.+Humor is good, although it has been done before.+Could be a decent title to try to get 100% achievementsCons:-I thinkOmniBushas an identity crisis; it doesn't know if it wants to be a fairly serious speedrunning/skill-based game, or simply novelty.-While the more skill-based levels are fun, there are too many that just feel random.-No camera, which adds artificial difficulty (at least with the nonlinear levels - which are most of them).-All of the 'cons' add up to it being overpriced.I'd just as soon pass on this one.Go forRoundAboutif you haven't played that yet."
,Recommended,415740,32690989,Posted: 23 June,all,Konasumi,"OmniBus is the pinnacle of the simulation genre, offering an immaculate, exciting gameplay experience with new things to experience at every corner. At the start of the game, you take the role of the most powerful anime bus in existance, Mr. Bus, who is on a mission to defeat his enemies and save America. You can also take the role of a variety of other anime buses with their own special abilities and movesets.Buy this game right this instant. You will not regret it."
,Recommended,415740,23230209,"Posted: 27 May, 2016",all,Jansen :3,"It's been a while since I've played a game with as much charm and creativity as this one. Though the story mode might be on the short side, every level offers something different. I was surprised by just how much variety there was, with some game mechanics being created for one level only. The dialogue given to you before and after each level is very enjoyable, and the whole game has a great goofy tone to it. Nothing quite like using a propeller, a firework, a jet engine, and a soda bottle to shoot yourself to the moon.It's not a very easy game, often taking one good hit to force you to restart a level. Fortunately, the stages are short enough and restart quick enough that this isn't really an issue. Though I must admit, having my bus almost jump up and spin around after hitting a tiny snag was frustrating on occasion. Omnibus isn't perfect, but it does have a great feel, especially when your bus of choice reaches over 100 mph.Though it may be short, there is a lot of replay value here. Each level hides a hat to collect, and there are target scores/times to beat in each stage. Not to mention secret areas to find. Plus, free-play mode is great fun - feeling a bit like a Pro Skater game in a bus. You can even challenge up to 4 people to a split-screen bus deathmatch.In short, if you're looking for a few solid hours of silly fun, I'd totally recommend this one."
