76561198067073796,Not Recommended,415740,23242213,"Posted: 27 May, 2016",all,raven_pride,"I had pretty high hopes for this game. The trailer was pretty funny and I liked the overall concept, so I preordered it while it was on sale. However, there are some major gameplay issues that have made OmniBus one of the most frustrating games I've ever purchased. (I do realize that OmniBus is *supposed* to be ridiculous and perhaps even mildly frustrating by its very nature, but there are several *unintentional* issues with the game that severely limit its enjoyability.)First, and most importantly, are the mid-air controls. The primary challenge of OmniBus (and, theoretically, the fun) is in recovering from the wild arcs that your bus takes through the sky after it's launched to the stars by bumpers, ramps, TNT, and more. However, the way the controls are oriented makes the bus almost impossible to land safely, leaving your bus's fate up to chance. The issue lies in the fact that the left/right keys (and A/D keys) cause the bus to do a barrel roll in either direction. A more intuitive approach would be to make the aforementioned keys rotate the bus horizontally around the X-Y plane. I also recommend increasing the rate at which the bus's rotation accelerates in the direction the user chooses; right now, it's extremely difficult to influence how the bus lands.Second, the physics engine is bizarre. I know, I know, weird things are supposed to happen in this game, but there are still obvious glitches that make no physical sense. For instance, oftentimes when my bus is on only two if its four wheels for a short period of time, it gets launched into the air without warning. Hopefully these sorts of problems are fixed relatively soon as players report them via reviews and the Google Form the devs provided along with the release.Third, many of the levels are poorly designed. For example, the bandit level (in which you have to knock over 9 bandit vehicles before being knocked over yourself) can be won by doing absolutely nothing and just letting the bandits run into you; they often tip themselves over as they collide with you, and when *you* get tipped over, the bandits keep running into you, which turns your vehicle upright. Another example is the train robbery level, in which the bus falls straight through the train tracks that bridge various plateaus.Fourth, the way the camera pans at the beginning of each level can be dizzying. Plus, there are often situations where skipping the camera pan offers a major strategic advantage at the beginning of a level, but there's no indication to the player that the pan is skippable (which it is by pressing the spacebar).Most of the issues I described above are very fixable, which is nice. I'd happily give OmniBus a thumbs-up if they were fixed - it isn't far from being a highly enjoyable game."
